id: llm-router-streaming-surface
title: LLMRouter.route_streaming + LLMStreamChunk + provider fallback
scope: feature
owners: [@TODO]
paths:
  - volnix/llm/types.py
  - volnix/llm/provider.py
  - volnix/llm/router.py
  - volnix/llm/tracker.py
  - volnix/llm/__init__.py
  - volnix/__init__.py
surfaces:
  - LLMStreamChunk (new value type)
  - LLMProvider.stream_generate (new abstract w/ default fallback)
  - LLMRouter.route_streaming (new public method)
  - UsageTracker.record (called once at stream end, unchanged signature)
dependencies: [workflow]

intent:
  Volnix's LLM call surface is one-shot ŌĆö ``LLMRouter.route(...)``
  returns a single complete ``LLMResponse``. Consumers that want
  to render character responses token-by-token (live chat UIs,
  voice-mode TTS, "typing indicator" UX) currently have to wait
  for the entire response then render it at once.

  This change adds a streaming variant at the contract layer:
  ``LLMRouter.route_streaming(...)`` returns an async iterator of
  ``LLMStreamChunk``. Every existing provider gets a default
  fallback implementation (one chunk at end, derived from the
  existing ``generate(...)`` call) so the new surface works
  uniformly across all providers. Native per-token streaming for
  Anthropic, OpenAI-compatible, and Google providers lands as
  follow-up TNLs ŌĆö each is a distinct decision about a distinct
  SDK shape and approves separately.

  The fallback gives downstream consumers a stable API to build
  against today; native impls are pure UX improvements that
  require no consumer-side change.

behaviors:
  # Value type
  - ``volnix/llm/types.py`` MUST gain an ``LLMStreamChunk`` frozen
    Pydantic model with these fields:
    - ``content_delta: str`` ŌĆö incremental content text. May be
      empty (e.g., a chunk that carries only metadata).
    - ``usage_delta: LLMUsage | None`` ŌĆö incremental usage
      contribution from this chunk. ``None`` when the provider
      doesn't report mid-stream usage; the FINAL chunk MUST
      carry the cumulative ``LLMUsage`` for the whole stream so
      callers can total spend without re-aggregating.
    - ``is_final: bool`` ŌĆö ``True`` only on the last chunk.
      Lets callers detect end-of-stream without relying on
      iterator exhaustion (which catches ``StopAsyncIteration``
      late in some async frameworks).
    - ``provider: str``, ``model: str`` ŌĆö populated on every
      chunk; redundant for the caller but lets observability
      tag chunks individually.
    - ``error: str | None`` ŌĆö populated when the stream fails
      mid-flight. The chunk-with-error MUST be the LAST chunk
      yielded; the iterator stops after it. ``content_delta``
      MAY be partial (whatever arrived before the error).

  - ``LLMStreamChunk`` MUST be exported from ``volnix.llm`` AND
    from the top-level ``volnix`` namespace via ``volnix/__init__.py``
    (added to ``__all__``), so library consumers can type-hint
    against it without reaching into submodules.

  # Provider base-class abstract + fallback default
  - ``LLMProvider`` (in ``volnix/llm/provider.py``) MUST gain a
    ``stream_generate(request: LLMRequest) -> AsyncIterator[LLMStreamChunk]``
    method. NOT marked ``@abstractmethod`` ŌĆö providers that don't
    override get a usable fallback.
  - The default implementation MUST call ``self.generate(request)``,
    wrap the resulting ``LLMResponse`` into a single
    ``LLMStreamChunk`` (``content_delta = response.content``,
    ``usage_delta = response.usage``, ``is_final = True``,
    carrying ``provider``/``model``/``error`` from the response),
    and yield exactly that one chunk. Pure delegation ŌĆö no
    duplication of provider logic.
  - When the underlying ``generate(...)`` call raises, the
    default implementation MUST yield ONE ``LLMStreamChunk``
    with ``error`` populated, ``is_final=True``,
    ``content_delta=""``, then stop iteration. No exception
    propagates out of the iterator. (Caller's contract: read the
    final chunk, check ``error``, decide what to do.)

  # Router-side public method
  - ``LLMRouter`` (in ``volnix/llm/router.py``) MUST gain a
    ``route_streaming(request, engine_name, use_case="default") -> AsyncIterator[LLMStreamChunk]``
    method. Same routing logic as ``route()`` (engine + use_case
    ŌåÆ provider+model selection, request overrides, semaphore
    discipline) but yields chunks instead of returning a single
    response.
  - The router MUST acquire ``self._semaphore`` BEFORE yielding
    the first chunk and release it AFTER the iterator is
    exhausted. (One semaphore slot held for the whole stream
    duration ŌĆö same as ``route()`` holds it for the whole
    ``generate()`` call.)
  - The router MUST forward provider/model overrides
    (``request.provider_override``, ``request.model_override``,
    routing-table model resolution) the same way ``route()``
    does. Any override that ``route()`` honors,
    ``route_streaming()`` honors identically.
  - When the resolved provider's ``stream_generate(...)`` raises
    (NOT errors-via-final-chunk ŌĆö actual exceptions during
    iteration), the router MUST propagate the exception. The
    fallback implementation never raises, so this only fires for
    native impls that misbehave (out of scope for Wave 1).
  - The router's existing retry+fallback logic for ``route()``
    MUST NOT apply to ``route_streaming()`` in this TNL. Streaming
    retry is its own design problem (caller may have already
    consumed partial output) and ships in a follow-up TNL if
    needed.

  # Ledger entry timing
  - ``LLMRouter.route_streaming`` MUST call
    ``self._tracker.record(request, final_response, engine_name, use_case=use_case)``
    EXACTLY ONCE per stream, AFTER the iterator is exhausted (or
    the error chunk has been yielded). The tracker call uses a
    synthesized ``LLMResponse`` built from accumulated chunks
    (concatenated ``content_delta``, last ``usage_delta`` as
    ``usage``, last ``error`` as ``error``).
  - One ``LLMCallEntry`` ledger row per stream. Same shape as
    non-streaming. ``use_case`` attribution
    (``tnl/llm-call-entry-use-case-attribution.tnl``) flows
    through identically.

  # Phase 0 regression oracle
  - ``LLMRouter.route(...)`` (the existing one-shot method) MUST
    be byte-identical. New code paths are additive; nothing in
    the route() code path is touched.
  - ``LLMProvider.generate(...)`` MUST be byte-identical for
    every existing provider ŌĆö the new ``stream_generate`` is a
    sibling method, not a wrapper.

non-goals:
  - **No native streaming implementations on Anthropic, OpenAI-
    compatible, or Google providers.** Each lands as its own
    follow-up TNL because each SDK has unique chunk shape
    (Anthropic's event-based stream, OpenAI's AsyncStream,
    Google's generate_content_stream) and unique tool-call
    chunking semantics that warrant separate review.
  - No streaming retry/fallback logic in the router. Streaming
    retry has design tradeoffs (re-stream from scratch vs surface
    partial+error vs caller decides) that warrant their own TNL
    once a real consumer needs the behavior.
  - No streaming for embeddings (``LLMProvider.embed`` /
    ``LLMRouter.embed``). Embeddings are batch-shaped; streaming
    doesn't apply.
  - No bus events on chunk boundaries (e.g.,
    ``LLMStreamChunkEvent``). Caller-facing iterator is the
    surface; bus integration is a separate observability
    decision.
  - No new replay-mode handling for streaming.
    ``ReplayLLMProvider`` inherits the fallback default (one
    chunk at end from its existing ``generate``), which preserves
    deterministic replay byte-for-byte. Native streaming replay
    is out of scope.
  - No CLI surface change. Library consumers consume the new
    method programmatically.
  - No update to ``docs/embedding_volnix.md`` "what's in flux"
    section mentioning the streaming gap. That note can land in
    a separate documentation pass once at least one native impl
    ships and the streaming UX is genuinely available.

rationale:
  Splitting Wave 1 (contract) from Wave 2 (per-provider native
  impls) follows the "one coherent surface per TNL" rule from
  ``workflow.tnl``. The contract is one decision: "do we add
  streaming to the LLM router?" Native impls are N decisions:
  "how do we adapt provider X's SDK to our chunk shape?" Each
  provider's SDK has unique tool-call streaming behavior, unique
  usage-data delivery, unique error semantics ŌĆö bundling them
  into one TNL makes the review intractable.

  The fallback-by-default approach means downstream consumers
  can adopt the streaming API today and get incremental UX wins
  as native impls land per provider. They never need to refactor
  consumer code; the contract is stable.

  The "one ledger row per stream, written at end" decision keeps
  the ledger semantics identical between streaming and
  non-streaming calls. One LLM call = one LLMCallEntry. Caller
  can attribute spend, count calls, debug retries with the same
  query patterns regardless of which method fired.
